ens of thousands of years, new social roles—notably spouse, father, in-laws, and grandparents—have co-evolved with new technologies and symbolic meanings to produce the human species, in the absence of significant biological evolution. We are biocultural creatures, Marks argues, fully comprehensible by recourse to neither our real ape ancestry nor our imaginary cultureless biology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHuman evolution. 0aSocial evolution. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Physical.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  abiocultural evolution.  abiocultural.  abiological anthropology.  abiological evolution.  abiology.  acreationism.  aevolution.  agenetic evolution.  agreat chain of being.  ahistory of evolution.  ahuman culture.  ahuman development.  ahuman evolution.  ahuman nature.  ahuman origins.  ahuman species.  akinship.  aman from apes.  amodern biology.  aprimatology.  ascience and genetics.  ascience of human origins.  ascience.  ascientists.  asocial evolution.  astudy of evolution.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028581140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096119740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961197/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY